<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-670-559  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 670 559.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 26 1990 v219 n23 pS36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Finding fault with the local loop. (telephone services)(Transmission Special: Fiber Explodes into the Local Loop)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pfeiffer, Deborah.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local exchange carriers (LECs) face challenges installing fiberinto the local loop.andP;  For one thing, as fiber gets close to thesubscriber, splices and connectors get closer together.andP;  LECs areless concerned with long-range functionality, and they requireequipment such as optical time domain reflectometers (OTDRs) withshort dead zones and better resolution.andP;  And LECs must move fiberhandling away from the realm of the specialist.andP;  With more peopleinvolved, companies need more test sets and current sets cost tensof thousands of dollars, so companies are looking for equipmentthat is more economical.andP;  LECs need equipment that is easy to use,requiring little training.andP;  GTE, working with several companies,has developed an 'optical fault finder,' and Tektronix introducedthe first fault finder in 1989.andP;  The product's cost is onlyone-fourth to one-third of an OTDR's cost.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsTelephone systemsTelephone companiesTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>